Sure ğŸ‘ Letâ€™s start **from absolute scratch** and build your understanding clearly.

---

# ğŸ§  First: Why do ViewBag, ViewData, TempData exist?

In ASP.NET MVC / ASP.NET Core:

* Controller processes data
* View displays data

So we need a way to **send data from Controller â†’ View**.
Thatâ€™s where these three come in.

---

# âœ… 1. ViewData â€“ The Base Concept

### What is ViewData?

ViewData is a dictionary used to pass data from controller to view.

### Syntax:

Controller:

```csharp
ViewData["Name"] = "Onkar";
```

View:

```cshtml
@ViewData["Name"]
```

### Characteristics:

* Key-value pair
* Exists only for CURRENT request
* Requires type casting for complex types

### Think of it as:

A bag of data that disappears once the page loads.

---

# âœ… 2. ViewBag â€“ Friendly Version of ViewData

### What is ViewBag?

ViewBag is a dynamic wrapper over ViewData.

### Syntax:

Controller:

```csharp
ViewBag.Name = "Onkar";
```

View:

```cshtml
@ViewBag.Name
```

### Characteristics:

* No need for key string
* Same lifetime as ViewData
* Cleaner and readable
* Still not type-safe

### Internally:

```
ViewBag â†’ ViewData
```

So ViewBag is just syntactic sugar.

---

# âœ… 3. TempData â€“ Data Across Requests

### What is TempData?

TempData is used when you want data available even AFTER redirect.

### Syntax:

Controller:

```csharp
TempData["msg"] = "Saved Successfully";
return RedirectToAction("Index");
```

View:

```cshtml
@TempData["msg"]
```

### Characteristics:

* Survives redirect
* Uses Session internally
* Data removed after one read

Used mainly for:
âœ” Success messages
âœ” Error alerts
âœ” Notifications

---

# ğŸ”¥ Core Differences at a Glance

| Feature          | ViewData        | ViewBag         | TempData     |
| ---------------- | --------------- | --------------- | ------------ |
| Type             | Dictionary      | Dynamic Object  | Dictionary   |
| Lifetime         | Current Request | Current Request | Next Request |
| Redirect Support | âŒ No            | âŒ No            | âœ… Yes        |
| Storage          | Server Memory   | Server Memory   | Session      |
| Type Safety      | âŒ No            | âŒ No            | âŒ No         |

---

# âœ… Practical Example

### Controller

```csharp
public IActionResult Save()
{
    ViewData["A"] = "Hello ViewData";
    ViewBag.B = "Hello ViewBag";
    TempData["C"] = "Hello TempData";

    return RedirectToAction("Result");
}
```

### Result View

```cshtml
<p>@ViewData["A"]</p>   <!-- null -->
<p>@ViewBag.B</p>       <!-- null -->
<p>@TempData["C"]</p>   <!-- Hello TempData -->
```

---

# ğŸ¯ Real-life analogy

* ViewData = Message written on whiteboard (erased after class)
* ViewBag = Sticky note (also removed after use)
* TempData = Message saved in diary for next day

---

# âœ… When to Use

| Situation           | Recommended         |
| ------------------- | ------------------- |
| Same request data   | ViewBag or ViewData |
| Post-Redirect-Get   | TempData            |
| Strong data passing | Model (Best)        |

---

# âœ… Interview-ready Summary

> ViewData and ViewBag are used to pass data from controller to view within the same request, but TempData preserves data across redirects using session, making it useful for one-time messages.

---

# âœ… Quick Memory Trick

```
Same request â†’ ViewBag / ViewData  
Next request â†’ TempData
```

